\fs56 \cf2 What I found.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5 The five findings below are the ones the data kept insisting on. They're ordered from the most surprising to the most actionable.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs44 \cf2 \strokec2 01 \'b7 Trust without comprehension.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5 This is the central finding. 
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  of users understand their app's data practices "a little" or "not at all", and yet 
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  still trust the app to protect their information to some degree. Three of the most-endorsed concerns, third-party data sharing, access by external organizations, and lack of transparency, were each named by 
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  of participants. People know enough to be worried; they don't know enough to be protected.\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs288 \cf2 \strokec2 0
\fs129\fsmilli64800 \up90 %
\fs36 \up0 \
of selective-loggers stopped tracking sexual activity first.\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf5 \strokec5 USER COHORT \'b7 N = 4 SELECTIVE LOGGERS\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs44 \cf2 \strokec2 02 \'b7 Sexual activity is the canary.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5 Of the users who selectively stopped logging specific data types, \cf2 \strokec2 all of them stopped tracking sexual activity first.\cf5 \strokec5  Not symptoms. Not mood. Not cycle dates. The most legally sensitive category in the post-Roe landscape is the first thing that gets pulled. It's a tiny subgroup, but it's a perfectly aligned tiny subgroup, and that uniformity is its own signal.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs44 \cf2 \strokec2 03 \'b7 App data is already in the exam room.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf2 All 44 clinicians\cf5 \strokec5  in the cohort reported that patients had initiated discussion of menstrual app use with them. 
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  see it monthly or more often. App-generated data isn't adjacent to clinical care anymore, it's inside the exam room. Most clinicians still recommend apps to patients (
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  frequently, 
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  sometimes) despite naming patient anxiety and data accuracy as their top concerns.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs44 \cf2 \strokec2 04 \'b7 Users and clinicians want the same things.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5 The policy alignment between the two cohorts is the most striking pattern in the dataset. Transparency, plain-language disclosures, restrictions on third-party sharing, and user control over deletion were the top requests across both. 
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  of clinicians' open-ended responses asked specifically for HIPAA-like standards. Single-cohort work would have missed this entirely.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs44 \cf2 \strokec2 05 \'b7 Sociopolitical events shift behavior, slowly, and unevenly.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  of users reported that public discussions or external events had affected how they use their app. Reading privacy policies more carefully was the most common response, followed by deleting an app, changing what they tracked, and switching providers. 
\fs33 \cf3 \strokec3 0%
\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5  of clinicians reported that legal and political developments had influenced their own clinical discussions. The two populations are moving in parallel, toward more caution, not toward more compliance.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs56 \cf2 \strokec2 What it means.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 Trust is not binary.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \strokec5 It is technical, institutional, and emotional at the same time, and these dimensions can be in direct conflict. Designing for trust starts with designing for comprehension, not with a friendlier color palette.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \strokec2 Two-cohort designs surface system-level patterns.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \strokec5 Running parallel user and clinician studies revealed cross-population alignment on policy priorities that single-cohort work would have missed entirely. The methodology is the finding here, too.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \strokec2 Sole-coder qualitative work needs reflexivity infrastructure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \strokec5 I documented analytic decisions in coding memos and consulted my advisor at every milestone. In future work I'd add a second coder for inter-rater reliability, and I'd recommend it as a baseline for thesis-scale projects of this kind.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs56 \cf2 \strokec2 Where this goes next.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
