\fs22 \cf25 \cb26 \strokec25 FROM RESEARCH TO ADVOCACY\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs80 \cf19 \cb26 \strokec19 \shad\shadx0\shady-280\shadr600\shado0 \shadc0 A \cf9 \strokec9 \shad\shadx0\shady-280\shadr600\shado0 \shadc0 Femtech\cf19 \strokec19 \shad\shadx0\shady-280\shadr600\shado0 \shadc0  app for policy & user advocacy.\cb1 \shad\shadx0\shady-280\shadr600\shado0 \shadc0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs56 \cf2 \strokec2 \shad0 Beyond the study, an app built on the findings\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5 Alongside my formal thesis, I am designing and prototyping a \cf2 \strokec2 Femtech period-tracking application\cf5 \strokec5  as the applied half of this research, a product whose foundational UX is informed entirely by what users and clinicians told us they need. The thesis surfaces the problem; this concept surfaces a credible answer to it, with policy advocacy and user agency as first-class design constraints rather than fine-print compromises.\
The application is intentionally \cf2 \strokec2 not another cycle tracker\cf5 \strokec5 . It is a vehicle for the policy and trust primitives that participants asked for: comprehensible disclosures, granular control over sensitive log types, transparent third-party boundaries, and the option to delete with proof of deletion. Each interaction is a small piece of advocacy infrastructure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 \cb27 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf11 \cb2 \strokec11 LIVE WALKTHROUGH \'b7 WIREFRAME
\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs40 \cf2 What you're seeing\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5 This walkthrough is a wireframe prototype of the Femtech onboarding and core logging surfaces. It is built to look like a typical period-tracker so the policy work isn't marketing-coded, but every screen below the surface reflects a finding from the thesis.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\fs28 \cf2 \cb11 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Plain-language onboarding.\cf5 \strokec5  The first three screens explain in human language exactly what is logged, what is shared, and what is never sold. No 14-page policy gates the first cycle entry.\
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Sensitive-data segmentation.\cf5 \strokec5  Sexual activity, pregnancy intent, and symptom logs each sit behind their own consent layer. Users can opt in to specific categories rather than to the whole product at once.\
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Local-first by default.\cf5 \strokec5  Day-to-day logs stay on-device until the user explicitly chooses cloud sync. The choice is visible at every login.\
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Proof of deletion.\cf5 \strokec5  Deleting an account returns a verifiable receipt of the data removed and the retention windows that still apply by law, a direct response to the survey finding that users do not trust \'93delete\'94 buttons.\
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Clinician-share envelope.\cf5 \strokec5  Patients can generate a time-boxed, read-only summary to bring to an appointment, instead of handing over the entire account history.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs56 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 Recommended changes\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs30 \cf5 \strokec5 The five product principles below are the design recommendations the thesis points at, each one is implemented as a real screen in the prototype above, and each one maps to a specific finding in the user or clinician cohort.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf13 \cb19 \strokec13 01\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb19 \strokec2 Transparency before features\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \cb19 \strokec5 Move data-practice disclosures into the onboarding flow itself, in plain language, with comprehension checkpoints. \cf2 \strokec2 Maps to: 58% of users do not understand their app's data practices.\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf13 \cb19 \strokec13 02\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb19 \strokec2 Granular logging consent\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \cb19 \strokec5 Treat sexual-activity, pregnancy-intent, and symptom data as separate categories with separate opt-ins. \cf2 \strokec2 Maps to: 100% of selective-loggers stopped sexual activity first.\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf13 \cb19 \strokec13 03\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb19 \strokec2 Restrict third-party sharing\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \cb19 \strokec5 Cap third-party data sharing to the minimum necessary, with named third parties surfaced in-app. \cf2 \strokec2 Maps to: top user and clinician policy preference.\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf13 \cb19 \strokec13 04\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb19 \strokec2 Verifiable deletion\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \cb19 \strokec5 Provide a deletion receipt that itemizes what was removed and what is retained by legal obligation. \cf2 \strokec2 Maps to: trust without comprehension, users need verifiable signals, not branded reassurance.\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf13 \cb19 \strokec13 05\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb19 \strokec2 Clinician-share envelope\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \cb19 \strokec5 Generate a time-boxed, read-only summary for appointments rather than account-level sharing. \cf2 \strokec2 Maps to: 55% of clinicians see app data in the exam room monthly or more often.\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf13 \cb19 \strokec13 06\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb19 \strokec2 Policy-visible UI\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf5 \cb19 \strokec5 Surface the relevant FTC, HIPAA, and state-level shield laws inline at the moment a user logs sensitive data, so the legal context lives where the action happens.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 \strokec2 Status of the application.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf5 \strokec5 The Femtech app is a working wireframe / hi-fi prototype, paired with this thesis as the research-to-practice arc. I am actively looking for clinician collaborators and reproductive-rights legal partners to pressure-test the disclosure flows before any usability testing. If your organization works in this space, I'd love to talk.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

